════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
FIRST-TIME SETUP — execute when SESSION STATE is blank. Once only.
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

STEP 1 — Detect existing codebase
  Read: package.json, pyproject.toml, go.mod, Cargo.toml, Gemfile,
  composer.json, requirements.txt, Dockerfile, pubspec.yaml, mix.exs,
  pom.xml, build.gradle, pubspec.yaml, *.csproj.
  If config files found → skip to STEP 2 (existing project).
  If none found → check PROJECT IDENTITY Name. If it holds a project idea → STEP 1B.
  If Name is also blank → ask user what they want to build (STEP 1B).

STEP 1B — New Project Protocol (empty directory)
  If PROJECT IDENTITY Name already contains an idea, read it.
  Otherwise ask ONE message covering all of these:
    "What are you building? Tell me: purpose, main features, target users,
    any constraints (language preference, team size, deadline, existing infra).
    I'll recommend the best stack."
  Once you have the idea:
    1. Pick the best-fit entry from STEP 2 table — name it and justify (2-3 sentences).
       State 1-2 alternatives considered and why you didn't choose them.
    2. Ask: "This sounds like [Stack]. Should I proceed, or do you prefer something else?"
    3. On confirmation → run STEP 3 and STEP 4 using your recommendation (not code scans).
    4. At end of STEP 5, ask: "Ready to scaffold? I'll create these files and folders:
       [list the exact structure from STEP 2 for the chosen stack]
       Type 'yes' to generate them all."

STEP 2 — Load stack defaults (structure + conventions + security rules)

  node-express   → src/controllers/ src/models/ src/routes/ src/middleware/ src/services/
                   camelCase files · MVC · async/await · JWT + helmet + CORS + rate-limit
  node-nest      → src/modules/*/controller.ts .service.ts .module.ts
                   PascalCase · decorators · DTOs · Guards + Pipes + JWT auth module
  react          → src/components/ src/hooks/ src/pages/ src/context/ src/utils/
                   PascalCase components · co-located CSS modules · sanitize all inputs
  next           → app/ or pages/ · app/api/ · components/ · lib/ · public/
                   file-based routing · RSC · server actions validation · middleware auth
  vue            → src/components/ src/views/ src/store/ src/router/ src/composables/
                   PascalCase SFCs · pinia · vue-router · route guards · input sanitization
  angular        → src/app/modules/ components/ services/ guards/
                   PascalCase · DI pattern · NgModules · HTTP interceptors · XSS sanitization
  svelte         → src/lib/ src/routes/ src/components/ src/stores/
                   PascalCase · SvelteKit file-based routing · input sanitization · CSP
  django         → apps/*/models.py views.py urls.py serializers.py
                   snake_case · DRF · CSRF + XSS + ORM (no raw SQL) + permission classes
  fastapi        → app/api/ app/models/ app/schemas/ app/core/ app/db/
                   snake_case · Pydantic schemas · OAuth2 middleware + CORS + validation
  flask          → app/routes/ app/models/ app/templates/ app/static/
                   snake_case · blueprints · app factory · Flask-Login + CSRFProtect
  go             → cmd/ internal/ pkg/ api/ migrations/
                   snake_case · interface-based DI · JWT middleware · TLS · parameterized SQL
  rust           → src/main.rs src/lib.rs src/bin/ src/modules/ tests/ benches/
                   snake_case · Result/Option everywhere · ownership safety · ring for crypto
  spring-boot    → src/main/java/../controller/ service/ repository/ model/ config/ security/
                   PascalCase · annotation-driven · Spring Security · method-level auth
  php-laravel    → app/Http/Controllers/ app/Models/ routes/ database/migrations/
                   PascalCase controllers · Eloquent ORM · CSRF + XSS + auth gates
  ruby-rails     → app/controllers/ app/models/ app/views/ config/routes.rb db/migrate/
                   snake_case · RESTful · CSRF token · strong params · ActiveRecord (no raw SQL)
  flutter        → lib/screens/ lib/widgets/ lib/models/ lib/services/ lib/providers/
                   PascalCase widgets · BLoC/Provider · secure storage · cert pinning
  react-native   → src/screens/ src/navigation/ src/components/ src/hooks/
                   PascalCase · platform files (.ios.tsx .android.tsx) · Keychain storage
  graphql        → src/graphql/schemas/ resolvers/ mutations/
                   SDL · dataloader batching · query depth limiting · auth directives
  docker         → Dockerfile .dockerignore docker-compose.yml docker/
                   multi-stage builds · non-root user · no secrets in image layers
  database-pg    → migrations/ seeds/ db/ · parameterized queries · row-level security · TLS
  database-mongo → src/models/ migrations/ seeds/ · sanitize all input · no NoSQL injection
  database-prisma→ prisma/schema.prisma prisma/migrations/ src/repositories/
                   Prisma client · repository pattern · field-level encryption for PII
  database-redis → src/cache/ src/queues/ · TLS connection · auth token · key prefix namespacing
  testing-jest   → tests/unit/ tests/__mocks__/ · mirror src/ structure · no real secrets
  testing-vitest → src/__tests__/ src/__mocks__/ · in-source testing · coverage thresholds
  testing-pytest → tests/ tests/conftest.py tests/fixtures/ · parametrize · isolated test DB
  testing-playwright → e2e/ e2e/fixtures/ e2e/pages/ · page objects · no real auth tokens
  testing-cypress→ cypress/e2e/ cypress/fixtures/ cypress/support/ · fixture-driven · isolated
  ci-github      → .github/workflows/ .github/actions/ · no secrets in logs · OIDC for cloud
  terraform      → terraform/ terraform/environments/ terraform/modules/ · remote state · IAM least privilege

STEP 3 — Fill this file
  PROJECT IDENTITY   → infer from config files and package name
  STRUCTURE MAP      → scan, annotate every important file with its role
  SYMBOL INDEX       → key functions/classes with purpose (name + file, no line numbers)
  DOMAIN RULES       → ask user: "What would cause a bug if I didn't know it?"
  CONVENTIONS        → adapt naming table to actual language; keep semantic rules
  OPTIONAL SECTIONS  → uncomment Security/API/Testing/Performance if the project needs them

STEP 4 — Ask only what cannot be inferred (one message, numbered list)
  - Project purpose and goals
  - Domain rules and business constraints the code doesn't reveal
  - Current objective and where to start
  Never ask one question at a time. Never ask about things derivable from the code.

STEP 5 — Confirm and lock
  Show the filled file. Ask: "Does this match the project?"
  Once confirmed: stop scanning. Navigate via SYMBOL INDEX only.
  Write SESSION STATE to mark first setup complete.

